	   <a name=96655047211398></a>
	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f96655047211398><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=1&mid=96655047211398>Gimme Gudderarmur</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=1&mid=96655047211398#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <span id= >Anonymous</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Thu, Aug 17th 6:14 PM 2000</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[5.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Ok, there's no way by just reading that someone can become a better warrior. You can however gain useful information that you can use practice and work on later. There's no way I can go over everything all at once, and although I'm going to try, I'll try to be brief and go by sections.<br><br>General Warrior Information<br><br>As stated before, warriors should max all their skills, 1 hand blunt, 1 hand slashing, 2 hand blunt, 2 hand slashing, piercing, bash/slam, kick, offense, defense, taunt, dodge, parry, dual wield, double attack, riposte, and disarm. Your automatic skills, such as defense, offense, parry, double attack and riposte will automatically go up, but your other skills you must work on, it is suggested that you take the time everytime you level to bring up each skill so you don't have to try and catch up later in the game when you have much more skill points to catch up on. The reasons why you want to work on your weapon skills is you never know when you find a weapon out there that is better than your current weapon, and it might be one that you currently aren't using. Other skill reasons will be discussed as I go along.<br><br>Different Creature Types<br><br>When fighting against different types of creatures, always go against the healers first. At this point, the smaller races should switch to a 1 handed weapon and shield. You may be thinking, "I don't do much damage with a shield" your job as a warrior is not to deal damage. The reason you want to switch to a shield is because when you read the message, "A kobold shaman begins to cast a spell" you hit that bash button and it will interrupt the spell. That means while attacking you aren't hitting the bash button so you can save to interrupt the heal. Trust me when I say it'll make the fight a lot shorter if you do less damage and interrupt those heals. For the larger races, you have a natural ability to slam, which works the same as bash.<br><br>Casters are the next group to go against. Because casters usually have the lowest amount of hitpoints, they usually die quick. Although usually after nuking someone near to death. Later levels of casters will have damage shields and a shield skin that you have to knock off before actually doing damage to them. Again switch to a shield to interrupt the casting. If you have other tanks in group that are using the same tactics you can coordinate with them about who bashes when, ie. you bash the first casting, I'll bash the second.<br><br>Melee classes are the final type to attack. While they aren't as annoying as the other two types, they will usually take the longest time to defeat because of the large amount of hitpoints. Now you can switch back to dual wield or 2 handed weapons, which ever is your choice. Compete with others in your group to see who can keep the mob on them for the longest amount of time. When you get down to 2 bubs of health, and your healer isn't healing right away, before you get below, stop taunting and step back a second to get it off you. When you get below 2 bubs of health, the mob will frenzy on you. What this means is that no matter what you do, short of someone rooting it, that creature will stay on you until you are dead.<br><br>Warriors and groups<br><br>When you first start grouping, if you are playing with others that have your experience playing, you will find that everyone wants to do the most amount of damage all at once, or mana dump. When wizards do this they are usually running around with a creature stuck on their tail yelling, "GET IT OFF!! GET IT OFF!!" Well while they are coming back to get their body, inform them that they are nuking too soon, and to wait a little while before nuking next time. Also inform them that if they do agro a mob (get one on them) that they should just stay where they are until you can taunt them off them. It will be much quicker and they'll be able to show their battle scars to the hotties at the bars. If you see a mob break away from the pack to attack another of your group, such as a healer or nuker, simply disengage your current mob and attack this rogue creature. Taunt and attack until it's on you and then re-engage the original creature. Later on, however you will have to resist this urge to break away. Such as if you have a healer that is good at parking mobs away from the group in the absense of an enchanter. Parking mobs happens when an extra mob goes to a healer (let's use a cleric) the cleric backs away and goes to a safe place, bringing the mob with him. The cleric then casts root and roots the mob in place and the cleric comes back to the rest of the party. Usually by the time the root wears off the other creature is dead (assuming you only pulled 2). Another instance to avoid taunting rogue mobs is when you have a good caster in the group that is either doing the same thing, or stun/mesmerizing. You have to get a feel for what they are doing though, and after a while you will learn to trust your group members. As stated before your job is not to deal out damage, it's to take damage and keep the rest of the group alive. You will find monks and rogues doing much more damage than you, and you just have to accept that as fact. There's nothing you can do about it. Speaking of rogues, when grouped with a rogue, try to get all the melee classes on one side and the rogue on the other, keep taunting and keep the mob's back open to that backstab.<br><br>The final bit of advice I have for a warrior is don't get jealous of the other classes. If you envy another class because they have something that you feel you should have, then stop playing a warrior and play that other class. When you start playing a warrior how it's supposed to be played, people will learn that you are a great addition to every party. I say every party because you can't solo as a warrior. There will be times when you will be sitting some place saying "lvl 49 tank/dot/meatshield looking for group" and you'll be doing it for a while. Don't get discouraged as you will eventually get a group. If you make some good friends out there, you might also get placed to the top of that priority list. Send tells to friends and ask them to join, get into a good guild or just get a friend or two into the game to play along with you.<br><br>Good luck and happy hunting<br><br>Gimme Gudderarmur<br>49 Ogre Warrior<br>Erolissi Marr<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
